stylometry: The data mining method we used was clustering. I used data from Professional Development to try to cluster our students with like characteristics with different variables, such as age, miles from LEC, grade level taught, and classes taken at LEC. We first had to normalize/standardize the data, that way one certain variable did not overpower the others. We then had to set indices for the people used (I had data from 39 people; therefore I had Index 1-Index 39) in order to make it easier to look up later. After this, I chose to cluster the people in to four different characteristics (I chose 4 at first, I could have easily chosen 3 or 5, but later found out that 4 clusters was probably my best solution). After using the VLOOKUP function, MIN function, and MATCH function, and finding the sum to square distances,  I was able to see which people were clustered with my four "cluster leaders". After reviewing this data, I was able to see that the characteristics in each cluster group were similar. This could then be used for Professional Development to see the four different types of students they have taking its courses. This may help with marketing, etc.
